B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025      FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: Demonstrations and Prototypes accelerate the transition of time-critical Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR)
capabilities from concept to fielded architecture by reducing technical, integration, and operational risk prior to Program of Record
commitment. This thrust delivers on-orbit and ground-based prototypes that validate emerging sensing phenomenologies,
communications pathways, and mission data processing approaches in operationally relevant environments. By generating
decision-quality data and early operational experience, this effort directly informs Medium-Earth Orbit (MEO) Missile Warning/
Missile Tracking (MW/MT) Epoch transitions, Resilient Ground Architecture (RGA), and future enterprise architectures.

The Space Modernization Initiative (SMI) effort is critical to competing, maturing, designing, testing, and validating a system
capable of tracking emerging missile threats outlined in the Missile Warning Missile Defense Capability Development Document
(CDD).

FY 2026 Plans:
Test and demonstrate Low Size Weight and Power (SWaP), high bandwidth, agile crosslinks for MEO MW/MT Epoch 2 as the FY
2026 flagship investment for SMI Demonstrations. Deliver the necessary technical data to inform Epoch 2 of viable implementation
paths, provide prototype hardware for on-orbit demonstrations, and reduce risk to the FY 2028 launch and Initial Warfighting
Capability.

Exploit early development of novel MW/MT phenomenologies to prove feasibility for cold target tracking. Transition Mid-Long
Wave Infrared sensors, Event Based Cameras, and Middle Ultraviolet sensors into integrated demonstrations with mission
partners to prove new capabilities are ready to onboard into MEO MW/MT Epoch 3. These technologies are aimed to close a
capabilities gap in traditional infrared missile tracking.
FY 2027 Plans:
The flagship investment for SMI Demonstrations in FY 2026 matures into FY 2027 as the orbital vehicles manufactured by K2
Space complete integration and are launched into MEO. The current plan is to test Space Development Agency (SDA) v4.0
optical crosslinks in orbit from multiple orbital vehicles in MEO and in a higher orbit (in collaboration and coordination with SDA
and other mission partners) two years ahead of the planned launch of MW/MT Epoch 2. Space-to-space, space-to-ground, and
high-throughput long-distance communication links will be tested. In addition, the current plan includes integration of a low-cost
on orbit Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) sensor to pathfind high-throughput optical data pathways, to act as a pathfinder for
on-orbit track fusion algorithms in collaboration with Wide Field of View (WFOV) and provide residual mission capability.

Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory's Agamotto Event Based Sensor (AEBS), launched in FY 2026 in collaboration with
a mission partner, will yield data in FY2027 for detailed analysis, enabling the true evaluation of this sensor capability across a
breadth of mission profiles.


