B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025      FY 2026       FY 2027
Further investment will continue in orbital demonstration and prototyping of novel sensor types, including Mid-Long Wave Infrared
sensors, Event Based Cameras, High Dynamic Range (HDR) sensors, hyperspectral, and Middle Ultraviolet sensors to enable
cold-target tracking with a design for rapid iteration and implementation. Space Modernization Initiative (SMI) will continue to
seeking partnership and rideshare opportunities to demo on-orbit capability and reduce risk for Medium Earth Orbit (MEO) Missile
Warning/Missile Tracking (MW/MT) Epoch 3 and future systems.

SMI will demonstrate ground architectures to inform the requirements process that enable resilient, proliferated capabilities such
as phased array antennas (one such effort is with ThinKom), optical ground terminals, and other low-cost solutions. This thrust
will also explore Ground Station as a Service (GSaaS) demonstration opportunities.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 decreased due to realignment of funds from the Demos thrust to the Tech Mat thrust to optimize mission investments.
Title: Technology Maturation                                                                                                               35.153      10.876         24.621
Description: Technology Maturation develops and hardens critical component and subsystem technologies required to
sustain, scale, and proliferate the Next-Generation Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) enterprise. This thrust focuses on
manufacturability, affordability, resiliency, and performance advancements in key enabling technologies such as focal plane
arrays, processors, automation algorithms, and survivability enhancements. By maturing technologies prior to system integration,
this effort reduces cost, schedule, and technical risk for future OPIR architectures.

Assess technology needs to support resiliency of Program of Record (PoR) assets and future architectures that are responsive
to the evolving threat environment. Perform trade and design studies to assess obsolescence, affordability, capability design
modifications, and Concept of Operations (CONOPS) for the Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) mission. Mature technologies
and manufacturability to reduce cost, schedule, and technical risk for new component and subsystem designs that may be used
in the future systems. Mature technologies including algorithms, Focal Plane Array (FPA), optical filters, on-board processors,
auxiliary resiliency payloads, and other payload components for future missile warning satellites, and reconstitution capabilities.
Develop Modeling and Simulation (M&S) capabilities, and engineering model prototypes for hardware/software integration and
testing. These efforts will reduce risk and mature technologies applicable to future systems and architectures. Additionally,
develop test beds to validate/verify requirements and ensure technical maturity for next-generation payload technologies as well
as threat mitigation components and techniques.

As a result of the Space Warfighting Analysis Center (SWAC) Analysis of Alternatives (AoA) and Force Design, several key
technologies areas were highlighted to execute the Medium-Earth Orbit (MEO)/Low Earth Orbit (LEO) pivot. A detailed
manufacturability study was conducted in coordination with the SWAC during the AoA that recommend several critical technology
maturation areas.


