FY 2026 Plans:
The Wide Field of View (WFOV) system proves the utility of the wide area, sensitive, persistent capability with full frame, real-time
image data provided in support of operational exercises and tests with the Department of War (DoW), Missile Defense Agency
(MDA),and other targets of opportunity as available. The WFOV program will continue to provide missile track data to support
data fusion in systems that message out on both the Theater Event System (TES) and Integrated Tactical Warning and Attack
Assessment (ITW/AA) system. The program plans to create and test new specific data products for end users as requested
in support of Resilient Missile Warning Missile Tracking (MW/MT) and Battlespace Awareness/Technical Intelligence (BA/TI)
missions. The program is cooperating with the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (NGA), National Air and Space Intelligence
Center (NASIC) and others to make the mono-track data and full frame messages fully accessible and available for both near real
time and post processed intelligence reporting and technical analysis. WFOV is preparing to pathfind and demonstrate the added
value that Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) data could bring to several other critical mission areas and push the limits of OPIR
mission capability.
FY 2027 Plans:
The Wide Field of View (WFOV) system is an operationally-contributing sensor to the Theater Event System (TES) and the
Integrated Tactical Warning and Attack Assessment (ITW/AA) system that is currently positioned over the strategically-important
INDOPACOM region. WFOV is also capability that acts as a capability pathfinder ahead of Next-Gen Geosynchronous Earth
Orbit (GEO) (NGG), Next-Gen Polar (NGP), and Missile Warning Missile Tracking (MW/MT) Medium-Earth Orbit (MEO) Epoch
programs and will continue to provide utility of the wide area, sensitive, persistent capability with full frame, real- time image data
provided in support of operational exercises and tests with the Department of War (DoW), Missile Defense Agency (MDA), and
other targets of opportunity as available.

In FY 2027, the program will continue operationalizing Wide Field of View (WFOV) Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) data
and exploring risk reduction opportunities for future sensors. The WFOV program will continue to provide missile track data to
support data fusion in systems that message out on both the Theater Event System (TES) and Integrated Tactical Warning and
Attack Assessment (ITW/AA) system. In support of operations, the program will be included as part of the Future Operationally
Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) baseline and will provide updated software to enable the operational data string. WFOV
will also be improving our ground architecture for better availability and reliability. The program plans to optimize different missile
warning products for the operational and intelligence communities and create and test new specific data products for end users as
requested in support of Resilient Missile Warning Missile Tracking (MW/MT) and Battlespace Awareness/Technical Intelligence


